<Rate>5</Rate>< Text>
I like this one more than south coast location mainly because of the store arrangement.   This one has women's downstairs with men's and kids upstairs, each feels like their own department.  There's an escalator and an elevator towards the back left side of the store.  Registers at all departments but the main one is at the lower level.   When they're short staffed or not busy, you would need to be rung up downstairs if you're shopping men or kids. Hand sanitizer located at the entrance, and they have plexiglass deviders at the registers.  They also have announcement through their speakers to recommend wearing masks and I do no recall seeing a signs to require masks.  I could be wrong though...</Text>

< Text>
This Zara is a 2 story department store. The bottom floor is all women and girls while the top floor is split between Men and Kids. The kids section is divided between boys and girls with sizes starting at 3m.

The store is clean and well organized.  Staff are friendly and helpful. Lines can be long upstairs as there is usually just 1 cashier.

The clothing selection is trendy/modern.  They do a great job keeping up with seasonal wear.

Prices:
$ cheap
$$  moderate
$$$ moderately expensive
$$$$ expensive
$$$$$ luxury

Zara rates: $$-$$$<//Text>

<Time>1573074473007< /Time><Text>Zara claims to have exceptional customer service, which I am here to say otherwise. I have 3 orders placed and have them to be picked up at the store. I received notifications of each individual orders arrived at the store in Victoria Garden, Rancho Cucamonga CA on 3 different days (10/15, 10/15, 10/21). I came in to the store myself on 10/22 and showed an associate all 3 emails confirmations. She came back, handed me just 1 box, and stated that my other 2 weren’t there. She did not validate my ID. As she was walking away, I also realized that package she gave me was not mine, I immediately gave it right back and asked for a manager to look for my packages.

He repeated what the associate had said that my packages have not arrived at the store and shirked the problem off to customer service line. I called customer service and filed 3 claims on that day 10/22 and they promised me they will find my orders and that the 3 orders were definitely at the store. She said some one at the store will reach out to me shortly.

10/23, my Zara app showed all 3 of my orders have been “delivered” on 10/21. To my horror, I called customer service back that this information have been falsified by the store. I DID NOT come to the store on 10/21. I requested that if they have lost my packages or delivered them to the wrong person (most likely since no ID was checked on my end), I need a full refund on all 3 of my orders. Falsifying delivery status is unethical at the store level. Again, Zara customer service said they will investigate and follow up in 24-72 hours.

Today, 10/29, since no one has followed up with me from Zara, I decided to call Zara to see what the status is. The claim is still pending per customer service. I asked to speak to someone who is in charge of this process and the person told me out right “they are not available at the moment” and offer me another 24-72 hours call back. He also disclosed that every time I called , my case gets pushed back to the bottom of the inquiry. Again, I have no answer about my refunds or what is the status of the investigation at the store level. And instead of making it urgent, my case lost priority because of their lack of follow-up.

My 3 orders together total to $522 and change. For convenience and straight forward purposes I have them delivered at the store. It turns out, it became a scam. Neither store associates or Zara customer services have any clue on how not just 1, but 3 packages all went missing. The most disturbing part is the store falsified delivery status of all 3 on the day I did not present in the store (do please check your store camera).

Zara claimed to have a scanning process in place and assure that 3 of my orders were scanned in at the store. Then it is clearly there is a problem with packages handling and honesty issue at Victoria Garden, Rancho Cucamonga CA branch.

Since I have not received any of my orders, I requested my refunds. Zara customer service has not been helpful and I find myself chasing for my packages and now my refunds without any direct answer.

I clearly see now that if I let Zara take care of this matter, they possibly will follow up in a few days saying exactly what the store has falsified that I have received my order when in fact I DID NOT.

I write this to demand a follow up on investigation and full refunds on 3 of my orders. Also, I need everyone to be aware of what horrifying customer service Zara provide and there is no protection to the customer against the unethical business at the store level.

11/05/2019 Zara finally called and basically “apologized” about bad practice at the store . However, they REFUSED TO REFUND ME because the packages were picked up. Zara basically said:
“sorry ... we messed up giving your orders to someone else ... that person signed for it... and now you gotta pay for it... sorry again for our bad practice”.

<name>Taylor Seamount<//name>< review>
Carla expertly sculpted my challenging hair and the result was--truly--THE BEST HAIRCUT I’VE EVER HAD.  I have extremely straight, fine, and thick hair--very hard to layer into the bowl cuts and pixies that I love.  Without the money to spend at a high end salon, I’ve just come to accept a level of choppiness.  Well no more!  I thought the haircut was great halfway through, but she made it perfect--even staying at it past closing.  I also appreciated that she explained to me why she was using certain techniques based on my hair type and desired style.  She is an artist that takes pride in her craft.  She is a warm, funny, and multifaceted person and I had a lot of fun talking to her, too.  I love that she promotes her fine art and hair styling together.  She even sent me home with some complimentary bulbs from her other business--a plant nursery.  She’s amazing!  Can’t recommend stopping by Cali Barber enough.< /review>

<user_name>Luis Berumen<//user_name><Resp>None</Resp><review>YOU need to GO here.

After a disappointing haircut from a salon, I decided to head over to this barber shop to get my hair "fixed." It was not until I sat on the chair with Carla that she was able to point out all the mistakes from the previous stylist. Carla is an artist, and her work proves it. She was able to fix me up and make me look great! I was beyond happy.

Best thing about her is that she is able to point out how your hair is (i.e. the way your flows and is fixated on your head.) Not everyone can get the exact haircut from those online photos, but Carla is able to transform your hair to a photo worthy style.

She works with you along the way to make the cut you want, at times her suggestions and how she explains the way your haircut could be better is refreshing compared to other barbers. She sees how your hair correlates with the formation of your face and she works around that.

You will NOT be disappointed  here. She is a sweet Colombian woman who is a pleasure to talk to. I am definitely returning here for all my future cuts! 5 out of 5 stars!

<username>Imran Khan< /username><date>1563430740566<//date><rate>1</rate>< Review>
Nothing good about this place...I usually do not post reviews so quickly unless it is really good or really bad. Unfortunately this restaurant falls in the second category.

Starting from the call i made to confirm the time to eating the food, everything is a 1 star, pathetic experience. The person who answered the call said that I can eat in if I am there by 9:30, I arrived at 9:25 but she said that they are taking only to go orders. As i didn't have other choice i decided to move forward. with the order.

I had to repeat myself multiple times as she could not hear me, I asked her to lower the music that was blasting in the back as if it was a night club.

Now coming to the main part, i would have let all the experience go if the good was good..I paid $22 and it is not worth it. There is smell in the lamb and chicken, and not to mention everything was salty. There were no napkins, plastic ware or hot sauce. I would get better service at a good cart where i can get similar but tasty food for half the price.

Sorry, but this is not your place please find something else.</Review>

<user>100554470772592619525< /user>< Name>
TheOne Anjel< /Name>
< date>
1588996354451<//date>
< Rating>
3</Rating>
< review>
The falafels are good but hey can't make a good tahini sauce to save their lives . They think you're supposed to put hummus in it (their vegan version) or yogurt (I'm stumped on where yogurt fits with tahini). So, unfortunately you'll have to be willing to forego a good tahini sauce or bring your own. Also be sure and taste the fries before you leave if you get their fries because nine times out of ten they're unsalted and then on that 10th time you forget to check they're over-salted.
If the owner reads this I'm going to say it again cuz I told him to his face, why are you putting yogurt in the sauce? You'll save frustration and money if you forego the yogurt. find yourself a good recipe for a tahini dip. It last longer than something mixed with a dairy product and will not be violating the vegan delicacy.  At the minimum please stop putting hummus in your vegan version. Just tahini butter, distilled water, lemon juice and a pinch of cayenne and you have a basic tahini.< /review>

None</Pictures>

< Review>
Been going to this place for 32 years. Fairly Spartan I interior, but great food for a reasonable price. Falafels are actually spiced (you can taste the cumin!). Great yogurt sauce, decent pita and veg to accompany. Hummus plate comes not only with pita for dipping, but also pickled turnips. Yum! Burgers are also good, and the fries are great. < Text>
Came here looking for some halal food and this was the only place in the city that had it. The gyros and portions are really good. We got a gyro burger and a chicken gyro.

The burger gyro of course comes with a beef patty with gyro on top of it and my gosh it is something real fierce! The chicken gyro was scrumptious as well with the creamy yogurt sauce giving aid to the tender chicken. I really liked the food and would definitely come back here. Okay, that was a lie, I came here about three time already but it is really good.
Parking is hard to come by but I just park at Mcdonalds and cross over to eat here honestly. I knocked down one star because they only take cash and it is highly inconvenient to try and keep cash or use the ATM located inside their establishment to grab some cash. Amazing place none the less!<//Text>

The one thing about Santa Cruz, in general, is that there are tons of homeless people.  With that unfortunate scenario, you get lots of restaurants with "no public restroom" signs. That is NOT a slight against Falafel, but more against the City of Santa Cruz and their apathy toward this growing problem.

<Text>Very good falafels, and pretty cheap.  You get a large (6 falafel balls at least) sandwich, fries and a drink for something like $9.  The falafel had just the right crispiness and the taste was good.  Filling for the sandwich could have been a little better, but it was adequate....and the hot sauce was tasty and HOT!!!  Thick-cut fries that were yummy also.  Pretty much a hole-in-the-wall place, however, if you want a good, cheap falafel, this place will do!
Positives: Good, relatively fast and cheap.
Negative: Falafel "fixins" were pretty basic.</Text><Gmap_id>0x808e41d55d007687:0x423cd866ec55dbe4</Gmap_id>< time>

<review>I just want to start by saying I have easily spent thousands of dollars at Sprouts in the last couple years and don't recall having ever returned an item. In fact on a couple occasions I have bought something that was expired and I just threw it out because it wasn't worth my time to return it. A little while back I purchased 2 face peels I happened to find in the clearance section (one of them had a clearance sticker and one did not, though they were the exact same product). When I finally opened one I discovered they were both completely dried out, the substance inside was completely hard. And the expiration date was still a year away so it was clearly defective, perhaps that's why it was on clearance.

So I took them in Friday night to exchange them and just put the small balance toward my usual large purchase. The cashier said it was no problem, she just needed to get her manager Melissa to override it. When she came she initiated the return, but then she noticed there was a clearance sticker on one and said she would not return them. Her actual words were "look at the sticker, we can't return that". She said that Sprout's policy was clearance items were final sale. When the cashier mentioned there was a sticker on only one, Melissa loudly snapped "that's because she ripped the sticker off the other one". I was speechless and humiliated she would accuse me of something so tacky. Why would I rip the sticker off one and not the other? And if she had bothered to look she would have seen there was never any sticker on the other box. You would not be able to cleanly remove a sticker off of that surface. Also, you can actually see that the barcode under the sticker is blacked out with marker, which it was not on the other box, so had a sticker been removed, there would have been the marking. So either she is completely unaware of her own stores markdown procedures, or felt it would be easier to blame the customer rather than admit perhaps her staff was not appropriately marking down all items (which I've encountered there countless times) and to try to improve on that.

I said I did not rip the sticker off and she ignored me. Humiliated I paid for my items and left. As I was paying I read the return policy at the counter, nowhere did it state clearance items are final sale. I thought when she told me to "look at the sticker" that perhaps it said final sale on the sticker. It did not. Also nowhere on my receipt does it state clearance items are final sale. And lastly, Sprout's own website states "Clearance and Manager's special items are returnable/refundable in accordance with our standard policy". So apparently Sprouts doesn't follow their own return policies, and they can also sell defective products to unwitting customers and the customer has no recourse. And most importantly their managers can freely treat customers with complete and utter disrespect. I worked in customer service for over a decade, I never try to take advantage of store policies and I'm always extremely respectful in all my interactions regardless of whether I am the employee or the customer. I can tell you without a shadow of a doubt this woman has no business working in customer service. She is either completely ignorant or completely defiant of her own company policies and procedures, and the judgmental and condescending manner in which she treats customers is inexcusable.

Sprouts has lost a loyal customer and I will share my experience with everyone I know. There are simply too many options available nearby, NOBODY deserves to be treated like that.< /review><time>1570513682431<//time><username>Ari S< /username><rate>1<//rate></record>

< Text>
My wife and I pretty much live at Sprouts and it's not unusual for us to make several stops throughout the day. It doesn't offer everything we would want, but the majority of our weekly shopping is done here. The cashiers recognize us at this point and know us for our frequent stops to get food for our bunnies. Dairy tends to be more expensive, but produce is excellent and we enjoy the bulk section which allows us to stock up on popcorn, walnuts, raisins and occasionally raid the chocolate section.</Text>

<Review>I was so excited when Sprout's announced that they were opening a store in Upland. They have the freshest  produce and usually for less money that the other grocery stores. They also have a nice bakery and meat counter in addition to health foods, organic everything, bulk items like nuts and cereals, and much more. Sprout's is a farmers market on steroids. The stores are always clean and have an opened layout. No cramped  2 cart wide isles with 6 foot high shelves, in Sprout's you can survey the whole store as you walk in the front door. Sprout's is located in the well maintained Upland Square Shopping Center which is on the corner of Foothill Blvd. and San Antonio Ave. It's in the same location that the old Alpha Beta grocery store occupied 40 or so years ago.< /Review>< user_id>

< Rating>
5</Rating>
<Text>Evan helped me out by putting a Vintera 60s Jazzmaster on order for me, and he kept me updated throughout the entire wait. When it was clear that Fender was simply unable to give a reliable wait time due to unprecedented demand in 2020, we cancelled the order, no harm, no foul... and then he introduced me to the Strat that would eventually come home with me.

Before I even took her home, Brian did a complete setup job on it that included putting 10 gauge strings on, instead of the stock 9s. Makes a world of difference to me in terms of tactile response, since it’a what I use on all of my 25.5” scale guitars.

You won’t get better service than the fellas that work here can give you. They know what’s up, they care, and they do their very best to give you an experience worth coming back for. Even when I’ve been back just to window shop, I’ve wound up coming away with new knowledge and a good experience.

Thanks a lot, y’all. There’s hope for the future of musicians yet!< /Text>< pictures>

<text>Long story short: The Fillmore Center doesn't care about people who have been severely financially impacted by the pandemic. Details below.

I've live here for over a year and resigned my lease in February. Then the pandemic hit a few weeks later. My girlfriend and I both work in the hospitality industry and were immediately out of work.

Initially, I made some phone calls to ask what the Fillmore Center was doing to help during this unprecedented time. I was told to be patient and that they would get back to me. They didn't get back to me. For the past 6-months, I've sent numerous emails, filled out several forms explaining our financial misfortune, spoken with people in person. Invariably, these conversations have fallen on deaf ears, I've been ghosted, ignored, forgotten about.

It's now 6 months later and after paying our rent with unemployment money. We've hit a dead end and now need to move out because we can't afford it anymore. There are many cheaper options on the market now and we need to find something better. The Fillmore Center has neglected us in every way and is now telling us that we need to pay them 2-months rent or $7,000 in order to move on from this disaster. Was this stipulated in our lease? Yes, it was. But given the unprecedented times that we are going through, I thought that someone here would have some shred of human decency and understanding to find some kind of compromise.

Hospitality workers are getting crushed due to this pandemic with no end in sight. The Fillmore Center doesn't care though. They'll just ignore you and happily kick you in the gut when you're at your lowest point and have given up.</text>< Pictures>

<UserId.>117545889541474420116</UserId.>< user_name>
Clayton Kemp</user_name>
<time>1546750417501</time><Rate>1<//Rate><Review>I've lived in apartments and rented my whole life and this was by far the worst experience I've ever had start to finish. I just finished a 2 year lease.

First of all ask the leasing agent when the elevator was replaced in the building you are looking at. I had the unfortunate pleasure of going through the replacing experience. Long story short about a year of only one working at a time and occasionally having to take the stairs from the 14th floor, long wait times, and dealing with angry neighbors. It's like riding the bus. Several times the one that was working would go out.

Things were constantly falling apart in the unit. The main closet collapsed in my unit 3 times! Every time the maintenance people would say, "it looks like the last guy did a bad job". They are nice enough but don't seem to be trained very well.

Packages - By far the biggest headache here. Do not be fooled by the Luxor system, it's always a complete mess. The delivery drivers may leave your packages in 3 different locations on the property, none of which are your front door. Expect to be chasing mail around. over 2 years I had roughly 7 packages stolen or "lost" here.

Every time you need anything from the office staff they say,  "Oh So and so needs to answer that question and they are conveniently out to lunch". This happend to me countless times including the simple question of "what is my final rent amount" - This took 3 staff members to figure out and about 45 mins of my day.

They charge you a cleaning fee when you move out if the unit is not "market ready". My unit wasn't even market ready when I took possession. The vinyl floor was ripped and there was a huge candle burn in one the cabinets that took them 2 months to replace. My carpet wasn't new and had visible signs of wear and tear. On top of the couple hundred dollar cleaning fee they ended up hitting me for an extra $100 or so of my deposit with no notes or explanation. I called and they said (as you may have guessed from the previous passage), "Oh so and so needs to answer that and she's out, I'll transfer you to her voicemail". I left a message and got no reply whatsoever.

< Review>
I've lived in apartments and rented my whole life and this was by far the worst experience I've ever had start to finish. I just finished a 2 year lease.

First of all ask the leasing agent when the elevator was replaced in the building you are looking at. I had the unfortunate pleasure of going through the replacing experience. Long story short about a year of only one working at a time and occasionally having to take the stairs from the 14th floor, long wait times, and dealing with angry neighbors. It's like riding the bus. Several times the one that was working would go out.

Things were constantly falling apart in the unit. The main closet collapsed in my unit 3 times! Every time the maintenance people would say, "it looks like the last guy did a bad job". They are nice enough but don't seem to be trained very well.

Packages - By far the biggest headache here. Do not be fooled by the Luxor system, it's always a complete mess. The delivery drivers may leave your packages in 3 different locations on the property, none of which are your front door. Expect to be chasing mail around. over 2 years I had roughly 7 packages stolen or "lost" here.

Every time you need anything from the office staff they say,  "Oh So and so needs to answer that question and they are conveniently out to lunch". This happend to me countless times including the simple question of "what is my final rent amount" - This took 3 staff members to figure out and about 45 mins of my day.

They charge you a cleaning fee when you move out if the unit is not "market ready". My unit wasn't even market ready when I took possession. The vinyl floor was ripped and there was a huge candle burn in one the cabinets that took them 2 months to replace. My carpet wasn't new and had visible signs of wear and tear. On top of the couple hundred dollar cleaning fee they ended up hitting me for an extra $100 or so of my deposit with no notes or explanation. I called and they said (as you may have guessed from the previous passage), "Oh so and so needs to answer that and she's out, I'll transfer you to her voicemail". I left a message and got no reply whatsoever.

Security guards to walk around and occasionally run people off but expect sketchy characters at all hours of the day lurking around the building and in the common areas. It's also common to see random piles of puke in the common areas on the weekends.

Do yourself a huge favor and waste your money elsewhere.<//Review>

<Time>1585597801507</Time>< rating>
2</rating>
< Text>
As someone who lived here for 3 years, if you can I'd recommend living somewhere else. The units are nice and I enjoy the neighborhood—but any time you need to do anything remotely official with the leasing office/security/property managers be prepared for the most pedantic, procedural, robotic and difficult experience possible.

Moving in? Be prepared to have a loading dock scheduled and finish within exactly their time window or good luck finding a place for the truck, not their problem. Reserve an elevator? First be prepared that the other elevator will break in these old buildings—and for the security office to dock time from your reservation if they see you move any items before your scheduled window. Turning in keys? Everyone must turn them all in at the exact same moment even if you have roommates. Something broken? Maybe you'll get it fixed in the same week if you're lucky. Want to use their outdoor spaces or grills? Make a reservation by phone, walk a few blocks to security, and leave your ID. Packages? Be prepared to walk multiple blocks to their holding area, where you must pick up your package asap or have it sent back (if it gets there, and isn't just left in a lobby and stolen). It honestly goes on and on, my housemates and I really dreaded any time we'd have to do anything regarding management.

Don't expect much help outside of official guidelines, don't expect anyone to care if you're a good or long term resident, expect your rent to raise by the maximum allowable amount each year with the least amount of notice legally allowable. No accommodations will be made for you as a person ever—but they expect you to go above and beyond as a resident. As a bonus the fire alarm will go off and cause an evacuation probably once every few months (at least I got to meet the neighbors).

It really isn't hard to find communities even in the area that offer either better amenities for the price (seriously these units will always be priced at top of market, but the buildings don't add up), or smaller more human apartment management. 2 stars because I'd like to believe their generally all good people in a tough situation, it's just a bad set of buildings and bad company with likely crazy internal guidelines.<//Text>

<Rate>5</Rate><text>Very strong sunlight if your window faces East or West. Plants thrive.

Fast maintenance, though I went over a year with nothing needed. Chuck is their best maintenance guy. He's there like 30 years; he takes one look at something and knows how to fix it in 10 minutes.

Spacious garden / waterfall / bbq's between Ofarrell and Eddy Streets. In the center, the trees block all man made structures, and you can't hear anything but the waterfall. It feels like the middle of a forest.

They have security guards 24/7, and there is a police station adjacent at Turk and Fillmore St.

They use these water blasters on the outside of the building. It takes off the top layer and makes the buildings look brand new. The hallways and lobby have recently been redone quite artistically, though they haven't quite finished all the buildings yet. (Most of the rooms are renovated within the past five years with quartz or granite counters. It was a major improvement. If someone told you the buildings were brand new, you would struggle to come up with grounds to disbelieve.)

They also give a free annual carpet cleaning, if you pick one of the carpeted apartments.

It is hard to rent right now because Corona has large buildings like this refusing to let customers enter the actual apartments, and web cam's only show so much, but this development is a safe bet.

Highly efficient parking setup. They have a lot of empty spots, so it is fast in and out. It couldn’t be more painless even if you had a personal valet.
Excellent value overall, and excellent management always willing to hear your issues. Usually incredibly flexible. Familial corporate culture - it's like talking to your sister.</text><pictures>None<//pictures>< Resp>

< text>
Very strong sunlight if your window faces East or West. Plants thrive.

Fast maintenance, though I went over a year with nothing needed. Chuck is their best maintenance guy. He's there like 30 years; he takes one look at something and knows how to fix it in 10 minutes.

Spacious garden / waterfall / bbq's between Ofarrell and Eddy Streets. In the center, the trees block all man made structures, and you can't hear anything but the waterfall. It feels like the middle of a forest.

They have security guards 24/7, and there is a police station adjacent at Turk and Fillmore St.

They use these water blasters on the outside of the building. It takes off the top layer and makes the buildings look brand new. The hallways and lobby have recently been redone quite artistically, though they haven't quite finished all the buildings yet. (Most of the rooms are renovated within the past five years with quartz or granite counters. It was a major improvement. If someone told you the buildings were brand new, you would struggle to come up with grounds to disbelieve.)

They also give a free annual carpet cleaning, if you pick one of the carpeted apartments.

It is hard to rent right now because Corona has large buildings like this refusing to let customers enter the actual apartments, and web cam's only show so much, but this development is a safe bet.

Highly efficient parking setup. They have a lot of empty spots, so it is fast in and out. It couldn’t be more painless even if you had a personal valet.
Excellent value overall, and excellent management always willing to hear your issues. Usually incredibly flexible. Familial corporate culture - it's like talking to your sister.</text>

<Text>Pros - Near the Japantown/Lower Pac Heights, many parks within the vicinity, a Fitness SF gym right around the corner, some very nice people who work the Front Desk & Maintenance (shoutout to Samuel, Emmanuel, Dmitri and Jose), the interior of the apartments are renovated and clean (The last two are the only reason this doesn't get a 1-star review)

Cons - Where to begin. Living in the M1 building the past year, here is a quick run down. The leasing process is problematic to say the least and is a source of frustration and confusion for many former/current residents.  The building was supposed to be updated within a few months of moving in, took most of the last year to do so and looks like a flashback to an 80's rundown casino (I know I used to work in Las Vegas). The elevators are constantly broken and sometimes both at the same time so good luck with that. The laundry machines once broke down for a few weeks at one point. We once had blue water coming out of our taps (no explanation or heads up given). Also, be aware that the package delivery system is bound to lose one your valuables (never received any compensation for packages that were left out by delivery services that were subsequently taken by someone else other than us). And lastly, when it comes times to renew, you will notice that there are similar units in the building offered at lower prices than what you are paying, but management will make no effort to offer a concession (as if not retaining a current and paying resident is a more financially prudent decision than trying to get someone else to move in.) The low star ratings that most give here are completely warranted and if you move-in here and expect anything different you are surely going to be disappointed.<//Text><Pics>None< /Pics>< Response>
{'time': 1591140101721, 'text': "Hi Ricky,  Thank you for sharing your detailed review. We appreciate that you highlighted the hard work and dedication of our team members. We work very hard to ensure our community looks its best and our residents have a great overall experience. We are also grateful that you mentioned our clean and renovated homes. However, we are disappointed to read your other comments and are not aware of any blue water coming out of your faucet. Also, we do have plans to fix the elevators in the building you lived in. However, the state ordinance has put a delay on this, and many other projects were also put on hold. We really wish that we can address this and other issues sooner but unfortunately cannot due to the shelter-in-place notice. We are happy to let you know that the laundry machines were replaced with brand new ones about a year ago. As well, when the internet service of the card readers went down, we happily provided our residents free service for weeks until it was resolved. In regards to package delivery, we go over this in detail upon move in and it’s also outlined in your lease that states we are not responsible for our residents packages. We have come a long way with how we manage the delivery of packages and really put emphasis on resident experience. We understand that there is always room for improvement and we do have issues with certain carriers and their delivery policies. Often times it is the delivery driver that doesn't properly deliver the package. We have seen numerous deliveries left in the lobby, misdelivering them or leaving them in an open locker. Lastly, we offered our recent lease renewals the option to stay at their current rate. Each home is priced differently and we always try to work with our residents to find ways for them to stay at The Fillmore Center community. We never want any of our residents leaving our community feeling the way that you do. Please reach out to us if we can be of assistance or if you would like us to clarify anything for you. Thank you!"}</Response>

I'm not sure about most people but we prefer to not have our neighbor smoking so much inside of their apartment that our laundry room smells of the smoke, we cannot open our windows if the neighbor is home and I've had to tape over the old phone jack just to prevent the smell from coming into our place.  If we leave clothes in the dryer, they have to be rewashed due to the smell. I have sent repeated emails to Patti over the last three weeks and have yet to receive a reply. Courtesy patrol just simply knocks on their door and that is the extent of what they can do here. I've contacted corporate but even corporate doesn't return phonecalls.  We're pretty frustrated at this point and The Fillmore Center needs to get this issue resolved.< /Text>

< Text>
Leasing Agent: 5 stars
Apartment: 5 stars
Value: 4 stars
Application and Leasing Experience: 1 star

This review is not a criticism of the the individual people who work at The Fillmore Center or the quality of the apartments themselves. This is a review of the awful established processes and management I experienced as a new renter. Our leasing agent was lovely, but there were many things that were out of their control that were just plain awful.

It often took 3 or 4 days to hear back on an emails requesting any status updates on our application, and the updates were basically "still working on it". I called the leasing office about 6 times during business hours over the course of over a week and never once was my call answered. Voicemail every time. It took well over 2 weeks from the day we submitted our application to the day of signing a lease, even with me regularly pestering them for updates. This is about 2 weeks longer than it takes any other company I have rented from. This process should take 48-72 hours at most in my experience renting from Mosso, RentSFNow, and EmeraldFund properties.

The required application agreement is VERY sketchy and questionably legal... By submitting your application and a $1000 "Application Deposit" (note: it's not a security deposit) you sign an agreement that if they accept your application and you for whatever reason do not sign the lease within 3 days, they keep your $1000 as "damages".

Also, the leasing agents assure you all packages are handled by resident services, yet walking into the mail area reveals stacks of packages sitting on the floor in highly trafficked public areas.</Text>

I came in and signed an application and a lease agreement the other day. After paying the initial deposit and signing all the contracts, I was told that, pending approval, everything would be good to go and ready for me to move in. A couple of hours later, I was emailed and told that the price is actually 300 more dollars and that to make up for their mistake they would "give me an extra week to move in."

First of all, I'm not even sure that it's legal that you can change a price after the contract has been signed. But apparently, they were unwilling to budge and honor the price stated in the contract. I told them I shouldn't be penalized for a mistake they made, but they were unwilling to offer an acceptable solution. I'm sure this somehow goes against tenant's rights or fair housing laws, but we'll see.

Secondly, it seems like a total scam that they attract you with a great price, show you the unit, have you sign up, and then raise the price after you're midway through. Maybe it was an honest mistake. But you know what, accept responsibility and don't punish the applicant/tenant.

Luckily, I was able to get my full deposit back and cancel the whole process without being penalized. If I could give them 0 stars I would, but unfortunately you at least have to give 1 to leave a review.

With this experience in mind, I definitely will not be visiting this apartment complex in the future, and I caution everyone else who plans to rent from these guys. This totally astounds me. I've never had an apartment complex call me back after all the documents have been signed to raise the price. Ridiculous and unacceptable.<//review>

<rate>5</rate>< Review>
My move into The Fillmore Center over the past week has been a fabulous experience. I moved from Denver to SF and every aspect of this transition has gone exceptionally well.

I first worked with Joseph over a year ago when he gave me a tour, and he has delivered on every promise made to me that day. When my time was right to lease an apartment, we did the whole thing remotely and it the process went perfectly.

I have a fabulous studio that was newly renovated (all new appliances and finishes), incredible view to the east and I couldn't be happier. The building is quiet (concrete walls), well-kept grounds and facilities and I love the location. Great food and drink a short walk away, public transportation and quieter than living further east.

Joseph isn't the only Rock Star at The Fillmore Center. Everyone in the Leasing Office has been amazing, Danielle in Resident Services has helped me numerous times as I learn the Luxer Locker process, the folks in Security to help with reserving a freight elevator, etc.

My experience has been all that I had hoped for as I start a new chapter in my life as an empty nester in San Francisco!< /Review>

<date>1397148527109</date><Rating>1<//Rating>< text>
The only thing the Fillmore Center has going for it is it is located in a central location in San Francisco.

The complex is located next to a not so good part of town and it bleeds over in the area. I have friends that are frightened to visit.

Their security is there but not staffed accordingly to facilitate such a large complex. Cars have been broken into in "Secure Parking" several times.

The facilities smell bad. The stairs smell like urine the halls like smoke. Often times there are people smoking in the stairwell.

Amenities you pay for have been shutdown for half the year. They are renovating the BBQ area but gave no notice and they are closed for 4-5 months.

They are hard to get a hold of if you need to.

They have a shuttle to financial but it often doesn't show up. It is a pain when you have to be to work and the shuttle just doesn't show up. They have decided to institute a new fee for an ID system for then shuttle and they pass the cost to you.

They try and raise the rent astronomical amounts after your first year. 7-10%

They nickel and dime you with hidden fees.

When they sell it it sounds great. Then you live here and you realize it isn't.<//text>

<rate>2</rate>< text>
After years of insane rent hikes (the last one was $600/month, "negotiated" down to a $500/month, i.e. $6000/year hike) and not wanting to deal with the devilish leasing manager Carlos anymore I've moved. Glad to be rid of the joint!

I lived in the Fillmore Center for six years. It's an ok place to live, but there are some strong downsides to renting here.

The downsides:
- The management company does the bare minimum to maintain the place.
- The leasing manager, Carlos, is horrible to deal with. He claims to have no say as to what you're paying and just tells you to move out if you don't like the prices (I eventually did). They should just replace him with a form letter for all the use he is. One of the worst parts of the Fillmore Center.
- The apartments are old (around 25 years old now) but the outside, leasing office, and show apartments are kept to look up-to-date. Check out your apartment before signing the lease or you might end up with a 90s special!
- Rent goes up every year. Expect a 10-20% increase (i.e. thousands of dollars per year); that is expect to pay an additional month of rent or more every year you live here without anything being improved in your apartment. "We don't do upgrades to occupied units". Over six years my rent went up by over 50%. If I stayed another year it would have been closer to 70%.
- Everything in the apartment is of the lowest possible quality: the outside is kept looking nice, but inside things remain old/deteriorating.
- Service varies from great to bad. One time your issue is dealt with right away with a smile, the next it takes a week to get something sorted out, you can't find anyone who knows about what's going on, and everyone you deal with wants nothing to do with you.
- These apartments are expensive for what you get.

I kept renewing my lease because the apartment works well for me in a few ways, i.e. "the upsides":
- The walls between units are mostly cement so you don't need to worry about neighbor noise (yours or theres) too much. One of my bedroom walls was not cement, bizarrely, though.
- It's near entertainment: there are music venues and a movie theatre nearby.
- There's a nearby grocery store.

The apartments are sort of marketed as if they're "higher end", but they're not any better than your average multi-decade old apartment complex. Even the "completely renovated" apartment I saw was just new counter tops on decades old, beat up cabinets.

Examples of issues I've had:
When I moved in there was a ton of stuff wrong with the place as it hadn't been updated in many years. I had to get various things replaced and they just plain wouldn't fix others. I found garbage in my sink from the previous tenants. The paint on the walls was already cracking the day I moved in. There were cuts and paint splotches in the carpet. The closet doors don't fit the space in the wall so they are bent & kinked. The paint is of such low quality that a wet cloth can wash it off the walls. I had fixtures rusted when I moved in and was promised a replacement that I never got. There was paint splatter on the mirror I had to remove myself. I needed to clean layers of dust out of places. The list goes on but you get the idea.<//text>

< review>
Where do i start?!!  I literally just bought my house and was given the keys 3 days ago. I loved my 2013 Nissan, but i bought it used from another dealership a few years back and as a result, I didn’t know how well it was maintained. Well the transmission gave out and i was told it would be thousands to replace. So I did what anyone would do, I Called my bank who I’ve been with for over 30 years To ask for a small loan to cover the repairs. Because my existing car loan wasn’t quite paid off, they refused to give me a small loan to repair my car!! I couldn’t believe it, i have good credit, and I’ve never once Been late or missed a Payment on any loan I’ve ever had with them. I was more than a little  upset! I was outraged!! So on a whim i went to Lithia, and explained my situation and asked what i could do. Because i just put thousands down on my house i didn’t have much of anything for a down payment... and i still owed   on a car that wasn’t even running. Omar Diaz and Jorge Lopez worked hard to pay off my existing loan, and get me into a brand new car at a payment I could afford!!! I literally left near tears i was so grateful!!! They even arranged to have my non working car towed so i didn’t have to worry about it any more!!!  Thank you guys... for your patience and diligence to help me out when my own banking institution that I’ve been with for over 30 years refused to!!!  Now that’s service!!!! I’m now the proud owner of a brand new car!!!< /review>

The first day I came in, the sales rep seemed like he truly cared.  I actually thought he did.  I brought my kids in because I had to and they weren’t behaving well and he was kind about it.  They “secured” me financially on a car listed at 13.9k for $405/month for 82 or so months and my husband doing the math said it would be $30k over the course of time.  We turned down the offer, they tried to keep negotiating, but wouldn’t really lower the cost at all.  That was also with $500 down.  That day, I walked away.

Over the next few days, we kept in contact and they tried to keep negotiating.  I was interested in the car.  Multiple times, they kept giving me terrible deals that weren’t any different than the first terms.  I then offered $1200 down and asked about terms.  They said “$395 for 75 months”.  That was also near one of our previous negotiations that I turned down and that was with $200-$500 down.  The sales rep kept blaming “my credit” for the terrible 15% interest terms. And said they were doing their best and perhaps I should take the high payments and “refinance” in the future because I “need a vehicle to build my credit”, sorry... but I have one vehicle already that I’ve paid on time for 3 years.  I don’t need that reason to “build” my credit.

Over the course of the week, the KBB value for that vehicle had dropped $1k and I noticed it.  When he kept saying the terrible terms were my “credit”, and that he’s doing “everything he can to help, but his hands are tied.”  With that response that his “hands are tied” I asked one day what the terms would be like if they dropped the price of the vehicle $1k?  Since, that truly is in their control and could help me terms and situation.  His response?  “I could drop the price of the car $2k and it wouldn’t make a difference!”  I told him to prove it.  He sent me a quote for $365/month and I told him we could do it!  His response? “I’m not going to the price of my vehicle $2k!!  I hope you find what you’re looking for.”   First of all, I didn’t ask for $2k, I asked for $1k.  You exaggerated the price and then pinned it on me?  He truly made it all seem like I was in a “hopeless situation without him” and he was doing “everything in his power to help”, until we discussed money and I asked him to give a little if I was willing to substantially increase my down payment.

I spoke with his supervisor, Sandy.  She told me she’d have a manager follow up.  She sounded concerned.  Zero managers followed up.  Two weeks later?  Text from Sandy: “Hey, we haven’t heard from you in a while!  Are you still in the market for a vehicle?”

Yes, I am, but I’m pretty sure you’ve all lost my business unless you can seriously be a better, less MANIPULATIVE company.  You guys completely play your customers and make them out to be a victim in a “bad situation”, that you are going to “save”.  It is manipulating their emotions to make a sale.  It’s corrupt and I’m not stupid enough to fall for it when I sense something feels wrong.

Customers, beware.  When you sit at their desks and they’re negotiating terms, blaming your credit, not budging on pricing, when playing the good and caring guy, do the math and look at what they’re trying to sell you over time.  You feel pressured?  Don’t fall for it.  Unless it’s your terms and they’re LISTENING to you, walk away and don’t even lose sleep about it.  There are other, better dealerships!<//review>

< review>
We were very happy that Lithia Nissan of Clovis was willing to negotiate with us on the car we wanted whereas another dealership in the area was not. What first impressed me though was the knowledge the sales associate, Gabriel, had of the line of cars of which we were interested. At the other dealership when I asked questions about the car the answers given were guesses or assumptions by the sales associate not the facts. Few sales associates in any industry rarely know the products they sell so I greatly appreciated that Gabriel did. He was also very polite and pleasant and didn't pressure us with hard core sales tactics which turns us off and will cause us to walk away. The manager, Vincent, who negotiated the contract, was very professional, friendly and easy with which to work. The much appreciated hospitality he showed us was unexpected and "above and beyond" type customer service. Once a price was agreed upon we then met with the finance specialist, Bobby. Despite it being very late at night Bobby was very friendly and pleasurable making doing unpleasant paperwork actually a nice experience. You could tell everyone there worked together as team which made our experience easier as I didn't want to be buying a new car in the 1st place but had to because I'd wrecked my car that I'd loved driving and was still in pain from the accident< /review>

<Review>This review is a success story of an initially not-as-great experience selling my used car that was totally turned around by some really great customer service from the folks at Lithia Nissan, especially Gurdeep Randhawa. Five star service all around.

My old car was on its last legs, and so I used Kelley Blue Book's "Instant Cash Offer" option to see what I might get. Almost immediately after completing that process Sandy Her got in touch with me. She informed me of a price range that I could expect to receive for my car and instructed me to bring the car in to be viewed in person before I would get a final quote for the vehicle. The communication from Sandy was great. She even e-mailed me on a day she had off work. Great service!

When I first brought the car in be looked it, I was quoted the lowest end of the range that I had initially received based on nothing that was actually seen on the car. For a few other reasons, I had some concerns about this interaction and left an initial review that was not very flattering. It was at this point, that I was especially impressed with how my concerns were addressed. Within hours of posting the review, I received a phone call from Gurdeep to follow up with the review. The responsiveness that he demonstrated was incredibly impressive. I reiterated some of my concerns, and I was pleased that rather than try to minimize those concerns, Gurdeep acknowledged some areas for improvement (even indicating changes that were already being made at the dealership to address my concerns). He also expressed a strong commitment to ensuring that my experience could be turned into a positive one. He remained communicative with me, even texting me on a weekend day that he had off work to make sure that I was comfortable with a revised offer for my car.

When I returned to the dealership to try again, the team was actually able to give me an offer 20% above even the highest end of the range I had initially been told without me even requesting it. I was treated with courtesy, respect, and compassion.

I want to reiterate that this interaction had to do with ME selling THEM a used car. They really had just about nothing to gain from this interaction. Nonetheless, the level of care and high quality customer service that they provided in this interaction assured me that if the roles were reversed and I was buying a car, they would be a fantastic team with whom to work. Many thanks to Sandy, Gurdeep, Vincent, and Earl for the great work here!< /Review>< gmap_id>

<time>1576471778539<//time>< review>
We found online "starter car" for our 18 year old and went in the business. The car was advertised by the seller as having the price dropped from almost $7000 to $4995, and that is sold "As Is". Same was specified clear on the car, along with the car specifications. After the test drive we went it to buy it, intending to pay cash. Jordan Creamer, the Assistant Sales Manager, started the process when we found that we have to pay for LoJack and for Glasscoat, all for almost $1000 extra. We told Mr. Creamer that we did not need these improvements, nor we asked for them. Also, they were nowhere advertised, so the business is now in violation of the "false advertisement" policy. Mr. Creamer said that he will try to see what he can do about it and left us to wait for about 30 minutes. He came back and said that he is sorry but the car was sold to a different customer that "beat our price". Useless to say that no new customers entered the business while we sat inside waiting for him. He offered to show us a different car in our price range, and after waiting another 20 minutes he showed us a "clunker", a car with all chipped paint and a big sticker on the windshield saying "Not for sale".
We will report the dealership to Lithia company, while they are carrying the name while being involved and very shady business.
Please avoid at all costs this dealership, an also please read other recent reviews. Several are relating similar experiences with the same employee.

I interacted with many people to purchase one car; streamlining the process and eliminating at least three of those people would easily lower the cost of their vehicles. I don't need to shake random peoples hands so they feel their job is satisfied. Speaking of price, expect to spend $2k more than sticker automatically as "all Lithia vehicles have glasscoat and lowjack installed" at a premium of $1000 each that cannot be waived. If I could write three reviews for the three main people I encountered, I would, but I'll attempt to do it in one. I will start with the best employee I had, Gabriel. He met me at the door, knew exactly which car I came to look at and was very personable. He was not pushy, was informative and generally a nice guy. If I said no to an option, he didnt try to push. He gets 5+stars. Next is the guy that did paperwork, I believe his name was Robert. Again, personable and was knowledgeable. He presented some options in a way that financially made sense to me. He gets 4stars as he seemed a little unprepared. Lastly is Vincent. He tried to act personable but one could tell he has no clue; he will insult anyone's intelligence first chance he gets. Does he know I have a MBA? Probably not. Should he? Not necessarily but he should treat people like they are not stupid; he tried to tell me that buying a car (liability) at x price and after all the payments would equal x+premiums+fees+finance charges is the same as buying a house (asset). I had to stop him there. If he has a degree, he needs to take econ again to learn the difference between an asset and a liability. If he doesnt have a business related degree, then why is he a finance manager. I am 100% sure a private use vehicles interest is not tax deductible as are mortgage interest payments. He gets -0stars.

As far as Lithia is concerned, this rating is null because I still bought a vehicle. I hope, though,  they can fix the one major issue I had explained above to meet the professionalism as the rest of the team I ran into and earn more overall stars. This rating is more of a "buyer beware" as you have to buy two premium options whether you want them or not. I bought the vehicle solely because of the low miles (18k) and fair price according to cargurus that essentially negated the two mandatory premiums.<//text>

The car was washed, but in no way were the stains removed from the seat. It seemed like the car was just ran through a wash and wiped down. I understand that this is a used/leased vehicle that they are "taking a loss" on. However I am still paying 14K for it. This is a representation of the dealership itself. If you're going to buy used, don't buy from Nissan of Clovis. Oh, and the vehicle came with less than a quarter tank of gas. Just prior to that lease expiring, I received a ton of advertising from both the Fresno and Clovis locations to buy a new vehicle.  I went to the Clovis store.  Tried to give the leased vehicle back, but they didn't want it.  Instead, they signed me into a new contract to buy (not lease) a new Nissan Altima and never told me that had I waited a couple of months to do this, I would have avoided an early termination fee.  As part of the deal, they told me they would pay off my remaining balance for the leased vehicle.  The check never arrived.  Finally, after months of calling and complaining, I was told that their sales manager had since been fired, and I wasn't the first victim.   Meanwhile, my credit took a dive because the financing arm of Nissan hadn't received the monies owed that the sales arm of Nissan promised me they would send to pay the financing arm.  Total and utter disconnect.  Next thing I know, I'm receiving aggressive calls from some collection company Nissan sends accounts to, asking me for $1,200.  I tried to call Nissan, but got passed back to the collection agency.  Trying to resolve this matter has been near impossible and involved many wasted hours of my time.  I have excellent credit that I've worked very hard to establish over the years.  Nissan were the friendliest people in the world when they wanted my money, but all but vanished when problems arose.  I would have been a customer for life.  I wouldn't recommend buying a vehicle from this company to my worst enemy.</review>

< Review>
On 2/7/15, I went to Lithia Nissan of Clovis and the customer service exceeded my expectations.   Prior to arriving I had received a phone call from the General Manager, Adam Marazzo and he was the most pleasant General Manager that I ever spoke to.   He engaged with me as if I was already one of his customers by the way he spoke to me and when I went  to Lithia he treated my husband and I like family.   He definitely earned our trust and because of the way he treated us he made customers for life.   Anytime you go to a dealership it can be intimidating and it is something that most people dread.   I can honestly say that we had a fun experience, yes a fun and enjoyable experience and by that we all had positive results.   I wasn't intending on buying a vehicle that day but because of the way we were treated and listened to us we felt confident in the General Manager that he was doing everything to meet our needs.   We were also assisted by Internet Sales, Ken Herzog and he had so much enthusiasm about his job and made a very enjoyable experience for us and he provided a lot of knowledge about the vehicle.   We purchased the vehicle without even doing a test drive.  The Lithia Nissan of Clovis is by far the best dealership that I had contact with and I will continue to do business with them.   You don't usually get much or any interaction with the General Manager but Adam was so on it and made sure that we were happy the entire experience.  I cannot say enough about him he did everything he could to make it such a enjoyable experience.   The list goes on, I enjoyed working with Kevin Cavin, Preddy and Jessica. Your staff was extremely passionate about their jobs.  I am loving my new 2015 Nissan Altima and I will be back and will continue to extend my experience with my family and friends.
